      "narrative": "# CORRUPTION BRIEF: Boeing / NASA Contract Awards\n**Date:** 2026-05-06 | **Source:** Federal Contract Records | **Score:** 95/100\n\n---\n\nBoeing received two NASA contract awards totaling approximately **$32.9 billion** ($22.4B + $10.5B), representing one of the largest single-day federal aerospace contract concentrations awarded to a single contractor on record. Boeing maintains active lobbying expenditures exceeding **$15 million annually** and has contributed to members of the Senate Commerce, Science, and Transportation Committee and House Science, Space, and Technology Committee — the bodies with direct NASA authorization and appropriations oversight. The awards follow Boeing's **Space Launch System (SLS) cost overrun history**, in which the program exceeded initial budgets by over **$6 billion** with minimal competitive rebidding, a pattern documented by NASA's Office of Inspector General in reports issued in 2022 and 2023. Boeing has received over **$60 billion** in federal contracts in the preceding decade while simultaneously facing documented regulatory failures across commercial aviation, satellite, and crewed spaceflight programs, establishing a consistent pattern of sustained federal award flow independent of performance metrics.\n\n---\n\n**⚠️ Editorial Note:** This brief reflects documented public contract and lobbying records. The trading signal metadata attached to this query reflects a financial algorithm — readers should not conflate contract reporting with investment advice.\n\n*Sources: NASA FPDS, OpenSecrets, NASA OIG 2022-2023, USASpending.gov*"
